The paper is about mechanism design, which is a subfield of game theory (cs.GT). The focus is on single-parameter environments, which are often studied in the context of combinatorial auctions and matching markets, suggesting a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of black-box transformations, which are a common tool in algorithmic mechanism design and optimization (cs.AI). The analysis involves the preservation of welfare, which is a key concept in machine learning and optimization (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with private valuations, which are a central topic in information theory and cryptography (cs.IT).
